UNET Road Feature Extraction using Deep learning¶

  • 🔬 Data Science | Artificial Intelligence
  • 🥠 Deep Learning and Object/Instance Segmentation
  • Kevin Muhia Gathogo

Introduction¶

UNET Classifier has the concept of an encoder and decoder architecture, a contracting encoder side on the left and an expanding decoder on the right. The input image tile flattened as a vector is convolved by an unpadded 3x3 kernel, stride 1x1 using the formula “ o = (i - k) + 1 For any i and k, and for s = 1 and p = 0, where I is the square input, k is the kernel square and s, stride on both axes” (Vincent & Francesco, 2016). i.e., i= 572, k= 3, s=1 thus multi-channel 64 derived from (572-3) +1 = 570, similarly the last output 568. This is the same convolution across the channel before passing an activation function RELU. Kernel being a measure of the translation of the input image with stride determining the amount of information retained (Vincent & Francesco, 2016) and (Ronneberger , et al., n.d.)

Max pooling operation, down samples the last channel by 2. Again, convolution occurs creating several multi-channel feature maps before again passing through the convolution operation discussed previously.

We will be using a raster Imagery from LiDAR point cloud Rasterization . The source of the data is Public Works Authority (Ashghal) Qatar. Our study area is Wakra Road, The derived Imagery has a spatia; resolution of 0.1m (10cm)

The goal is to learn a UNETclassifier which is a pixel based model, to learn different classes of roads features and compare UNET metrics with other models metric to achieve the follwoing objective:

  • Model for road asset classification
  • Best model based on precision, recall and F1-score
  • Usage of the best model in a GIS Pipelined process of vectorising the feature.

Prepare Data¶

We specify the path to our training data and a few hyper parameters.

path: path of folder containing training data.
chip_size: Same as per specified while exporting training data
batch_size: No of images your model will train on each step inside an epoch, it directly depends on the memory of the graphic card. We used a 32 GB GPU

prepare_data function takes path to training data and creates a fastai databunch with specified transformation, batch size, split percentage, etc.

Find an Optimal Learning Rate¶

Optimization in deep learning is all about tuning 'hyperparameters'. In this step we find an 'optimum learning rate' for our model on the training data. Learning rate is a very important parameter, while training our model it will see the training data several times and adjust itself (the weights of the network). Too high learning rate will lead to the convergence of our model to an suboptimal solution and too low learning can slow down the convergence of our model. We can use the lr_find() method to find an optimum learning rate at which can train a robust model fast enough.

In [12]:
#Runs the Learning Rate Finder. Helps in choosing the optimum learning rate for training the model.

lr = model.lr_find(allow_plot=True)
lr
Out[12]:
0.00022908676527677726

The above method passes small batches of data to the model at a range of learning rates while records the losses for the respective learning rate after trainig. The result is this graph where loss has been plotted at y-axis with the respective learning rate at x-axis. Looking at the above graph we can see that the loss continously decreases after 1e-06 or .000001 and continous falling untill bumping back at 1e-02, we can now pick any value near to the center of this steepest decline.

Train the model¶

We are using the suggested learning rate above to train the model for 100 epochs.

The full training data was split into training set and validation set at the prepare_data by default the validation set is .2 or 20% of the full training data and the remaining 80% goes in the training set. Here we can see loss on both training and validatiaon set, it helps us to be aware about how well our model generalizes on data which it has never seen and prevent overfitting of the model.

Save model¶

We save the model which we just trained as a 'Deep Learning Package' or '.dlpk' format. Deep Learning package in the standard format used to deploy deep learning models on the ArcGIS platform. UnetClassifier models can be deployed by the tool 'Classify Pixels Using Deep Learning' available in ArcGIS Pro as well as ArcGIS Enterprise.

We used the save() method to save the model and by default it was saved to a folder 'models' inside our training data folder itself.
